{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"The plane.translate method subtracts (the normal parallel component of) the offset from d both in three and in MathGeoLib:\r\n\r\nhttps:\/\/github.com\/juj\/MathGeoLib\/blob\/master\/src\/Geometry\/Plane.cpp#L141\r\nhttps:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/blob\/dev\/src\/math\/Plane.js#L221\r\n\r\nNot sure what it means exactly but it seems inconsistent with distanceToPoint using different signs in both.\r\n\r\nIs d is the distance of the plane from the origin (along the normal) ? It seems it is the negated distance (along the normal):\r\n\r\nhttps:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/blob\/dev\/src\/math\/Plane.js#L35\r\n\r\nMathGeoLib does not negate:\r\n\r\nhttps:\/\/github.com\/juj\/MathGeoLib\/blob\/master\/src\/Geometry\/Plane.cpp#L98\r\n\r\nSo perhaps MathGeoLib and three could have different semantics for d (or for which side of the plane has positive distances).\r\n","created_at":"2017-03-08T15:17:13.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10957#issuecomment-285068811","id":285068811,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10957","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI4NTA2ODgxMQ==","updated_at":"2017-03-08T15:17:13.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/285068811","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/andreasplesch\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/andreasplesch\/events{\/privacy}","ava